BUT, that doesn’t mean you can’t fly alone with them. It’s hard, but totally doable. Here are the tips I used to fly alone yesterday with Cal, who is 14 months old. It was a four and a half hour flight time (from boarding to landing) and he only cried the last 10 minutes or so. But as our neighbors in the next seat said…EVERYONE was ready to cry at that point 😂

In the midst of neon colored Easter eggs and an extreme amount of sugar, we tried to teach the kids what Easter is truly all about. 

“Can you say resurrection?”

Easton: “Desurrection”

And that’s probably as close as we’ll get this year😂

But even though Easter isn’t about the delicious chocolate eggs or toy-filled baskets, it IS about them, isn’t it?

The little kids who are innocent-eyed and sweet, always curious and ever seeking. 

We’re to come to Him like a child, just like they do. 

And I’m thankful for that resurrection (or, desurrection) that let’s us live with our families forever and have the second chances we need ❤️

Happy Easter from our family to yours🐰

When I think of my kids’ childhood home, it will always be here. Where within these walls, it was me they relied on. Where I held them and rocked them to sleep. Where I worried at night over their fevers. Where we barely left for over a year in 2020. Where lots of big moments happened - so many first words, first steps, first foods, potty training,  first school day. I could name a thousand firsts that happened here.

And while we’re so excited for what lies ahead, as I pack up the belongings, I can’t help but have a million memories flash in my mind. And one realization: None of them will likely remember this house. 

Maybe a few memories from my 6yo and 4yo, at best. 

It’s bittersweet knowing that we’ll make so many more memories in the next house, ones that they’ll actually remember, but that the memories here feel like they are being quietly packed away as well.

So I’ll take a million more photos and videos over the next little while, and in the future, I’ll tell them all about our first house where I watched them grow from my arms to independent little kids😭❤️

If you work with kids in any capacity, it’s important to know how to administer epinephrine! And even if the instructions are written on the side of the medication (or it talks to you like the @auvi_q) it’s still important to review because you’ll be in high stress when the emergency is happening. Just remember no matter which kind you’re using: take it out of the capsule, pull the pin, and inject. Auvi Q’s pin is on the same side as the needle. Epi pen’s pin is on the opposite side of the needle.

This was our allergist’s advice AFTER his egg allergy diagnosis and BEFORE he reacted to peanuts. Those with egg allergies are at risk for peanut allergies. You often see these allergies linked, so if your little one has had a reaction to egg, try to slowly introduce peanuts as soon as possible!

Even with trying to introduce peanuts slowly, it didn’t work for us. We go back next month for a follow up where they will test him again! He’s been peanut free for 9 months now🥜

Vitiligo still exists in those with light skin - but it can be harder to notice! I was diagnosed around age 8, which means I’ve had my vitiligo diagnosis for two decades now 🤯

When I get darker in the summer, it becomes a bit easier to see it, but all of my life I’ve often been asked if I’m peeling from a sunburn😆🙂

But I’m not! I’m simply living with vitiligo. My son’s pediatrician told me I looked pale and probably had anemia. I was like “Yeah, maybe… Or it could be I have vitiligo😂”

Anyway, it’s been a while since I’ve posted about it!🤍

Let’s talk food allergy prevention! Sometimes, allergies are unavoidable. Other times, there are things you can do to help prevent a food allergy! These three tips are the recommended steps based on the best current food allergy research.

1. Introduce allergens early! And often! There are products that can help you introduce allergens. We didn’t use any so I can’t recommend them, but they exist!

2. Take care of your child’s eczema. Not an ad, but we love @the.bebaby cream that was created by an allergist! I’ve personally used it myself and used it on Cal. It doesn’t burn, it’s not greasy like other brands, but it really helps to soothe spots that are flaring up!

3. Don’t avoid certain foods while pregnant and breastfeeding unless your child has had a reaction and the allergist recommends you avoid it. 

Food allergies are so tough, and I’m not at all offended that people ask me how to prevent their kid from reacting like mine haha, I wish he didn’t react like this too!😂❤️

.
